    {
      "id": "b6522aea68d73e242c9a7b05878f2f69dd6492d8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 419,
        "name": "Frank Zago",
        "email": "fzago@cray.com",
        "username": "fzago.cray"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-16 22:13:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\nThe only symbols needed by liblustreapi from libcfs.a are strlcpy and strlcat. Integrating libcfs.a into liblustreapi cause 2 new issues:\n\n\n* strlcpy and strlcat are now provided by linking to liblustreapi, which can create a conflict with programs also linking with libbsd, which is the regular provider of these two functions.\n\n\n* every program now also has to link against libreadline, even if they don't need it. Additionally, libreadline being a GPL library, other program will have to either convert to GPL, or create a fake libreadline library. In either this is not desirable.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "5956eaa3af93c28b73a3d8c2aafb8783f93ba557",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-16 22:55:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI agree. I'm rethinking what I'm doing. The problem with readline is due to parser from libcfs. I should break that out into libcfs.a and keep the reset in libcfsutil.a instead. Eventually the parser will go away. True you could get a conflict due to libbsd but the autoconf system should detect strlcpy and not build those functions instead. Its one of reason I merged into libcfsutil.a since if strlcpy is present then libcfs.a ended up empty. Now liblustreapi does need the strlcpy functions which is why I directly linked it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "95ef918fb4b8f07b8210041e0f22e0026695bda3",
      "author": {
